    • example: Setapak -> Kuala Lumpur
In [ ]:
geoLoc = Nominatim(user_agent="GetLoc")
     
def locName(coord):
    address = geoLoc.reverse(coord)
    address = str(address)
    return address

def getArea(address):
    add = address.split(',')
    
    #data less then 4 item, will be taking the last 3 items.
    if len(add) < 4:
        return add[-3]
    
    #assuming last 4 is the area
    else:
        return add[-4]

Extracting time information¶

  • Time of the day (Morning, Afternoon, Evening, Night)
  • Round the time for merging
  • Get the Days info (Mon, Tue, Wed, ...)
In [ ]:
def cleanTime(data):
    data = data.replace(';', ':')  
    return data

def getDay(day):
    data = pd.to_datetime(day,format='%d/%m/%Y')
    return calendar.day_name[data.weekday()]

def getTimeOfTheDay(time):
    data = pd.to_datetime(time,format='%H:%M:%S')
    hours = data.hour
    if hours < 12:
        return 'Morning'
    elif hours < 17:
        return 'Afternoon'
    elif hours < 21:
        return 'Evening'
    else:
        return 'Night'
    
def roundTime(time):
    data = pd.to_datetime(time,format='%H:%M:%S')
    if (data.minute >= 30):
        data = str((data.hour+1))+":00:00"
    else:
        data = str((data.hour))+":00:00"
    
    if data == "24:00:00":
        data = "00:00:00"
    
    data = pd.to_datetime(data,format='%H:%M:%S')
    return data.strftime('%H:%M:%S')

def ranking(ranks, names, order=1):
    minmax = MinMaxScaler()
    ranks = minmax.fit_transform(order*np.array([ranks]).T).T[0]
    ranks = map(lambda x: round(x,2), ranks)
    return dict(zip(names, ranks))

boruta.fit(X.values, y.values.ravel())

2.3 Features comparison¶

In [26]:
%matplotlib inline
feature_list = ['boruta', 'rfe']
feature_num, acc_rfe, acc_boruta =[],[],[]

for i in range(1, 20):
    feature_num.append(i)
    for feature in feature_list:
        
        # Create X and y dataset
        y = df_encode['buyDrink']
        X = df_encode.drop('buyDrink', axis = 1)
        
        clf = GaussianNB()
  
        if feature == 'boruta':
            cols = boruta_score.Features[0:i]
            X = X[cols].copy()

            # Split data
            X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.3, stratify = y)

            clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
            y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)

            acc = round((accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)*100), 2)
            acc_boruta.append(acc)

        elif feature == 'rfe':
            cols = rfe_score.Features[0:i]
            X = X[cols].copy()
            
            # Split data
            X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.3, stratify = y)

            clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
            y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)

            acc = round((accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)*100), 2)
            acc_rfe.append(acc)
            
boruta_acc_result = pd.DataFrame(list(zip(feature_num,acc_boruta, acc_rfe)),columns = ["No_Of_Features","BORUTA","RFE"])
boruta_acc_result = pd.melt(boruta_acc_result, id_vars = "No_Of_Features",var_name = "Model", value_name = "Accuracy")

# Plot the line charts
sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(11.7,8.27)})

ax = sns.lineplot(x = "No_Of_Features", y = "Accuracy", hue = "Model", data = boruta_acc_result)
ax.set(ylim=(0, 100))
ax.set(title="Accuracy Trend for Different Feature Selections")
plt.show()

From the average accuracy of both models shown above, there is a difference between different models for the prediction, the average accuracy of the Naive Bayes classifier is higher than the XGBoost classifier.¶

There is also differences in the number of features. For Naive Bayes model, using top 5 features will achieve slightly higher acuracy than the implementation of the top 10 features; For XGBoost model, employ top 5 features will achieve slightly lower accuracy as compare to the application of top 10 features.¶
